The F-16 was built under an unusual agreement creating a consortium between the United States and four NATO countries: Belgium, Denmark, the Netherlands and Norway. These countries jointly produced with the United States an initial 348 F-16s for their air forces. Final airframe assembly lines were located in Belgium and the Netherlands. The consortium's F-16s are assembled from components manufactured in all five countries. Belgium also provides final assembly of the F100 engine used in the European F-16s. Recently, Portugal joined the consortium. The long-term benefits of this program will be technology transfer among the nations producing the F-16, and a common-use aircraft for NATO nations. This program increases the supply and availability of repair parts in Europe and improves the F-16's combat readiness.

I am not an expert in intelligence or foreign policy. However, I can tell you the moment I realised that Russia would invade Ukraine: it was when Russia had made clear‚Äîrepeatedly and emphatically‚Äîthat Ukraine joining NATO was a red line, yet the United States continued to ignore these warnings. This, coupled with the events of 2014, which many view as a Western-backed coup in Kyiv, signalled a turning point.

When Alastair Campbell claims that the UK is not at war with Russia, he is either mistaken or being disingenuous. It is now openly acknowledged by American officials that this is, in effect, a proxy war between NATO and Russia, with Ukraine acting as NATO‚Äôs proxy. The scale of Western involvement‚Äîthrough the provision of military hardware, intelligence, training, and economic aid‚Äîgoes far beyond passive support. Western leaders have used increasingly escalatory rhetoric, reinforcing the idea that this is not merely a regional conflict, but a theatre in a broader geopolitical struggle.

Moreover, this scenario was not unforeseeable. The Rand Corporation, a prominent American think tank, produced documents years ago discussing strategies to provoke Russia and overextend its resources‚ÄîUkraine was a key part of that analysis. While these documents were presented as theoretical policy planning, they have proven eerily prescient.

This is not to justify Russia‚Äôs invasion, but to contextualise it. Understanding the geopolitical provocations and strategic calculations on all sides is essential if we want to move beyond simplistic narratives and towards a resolution.

The standard Western position on the Ukraine conflict typically follows this logic:
‚Ä¢  Sovereign states have the right to choose their own alliances.
‚Ä¢  NATO is a defensive alliance and poses no threat to others.
‚Ä¢  The concept of ‚Äúspheres of influence‚Äù (where big countries dominate neighbors) is rejected.

However, this narrative often overlooks key historical context:
‚Ü™Ô∏é Warnings from Experts: For over 25 years, leading strategists-including George Kennan, Henry Kissinger, John Mearsheimer, and others-warned that NATO expansion could provoke conflict with Russia.
‚Ü™Ô∏é NATO Expansion: Between 1999 and 2009, NATO admitted 12 new members in three rounds, moving steadily eastward toward Russia‚Äôs borders.
‚Ü™Ô∏é U.S. Policy Shifts: In 2002, the U.S. withdrew from the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. Throughout the 2000s and 2010s, the U.S. installed missile defense systems in Eastern Europe, including Aegis Ashore sites in Romania (2016) and Poland (2024).
‚Ü™Ô∏é Putin‚Äôs Warnings: In his 2007 Munich Security Conference speech, President Putin called for a new, fair partnership with the West but strongly criticized NATO‚Äôs expansion and U.S. dominance.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Military Presence: NATO increased its military activities and deployments in Eastern Europe, further heightening Russian security concerns.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Ukraine and Georgia: Western efforts to bring these former Soviet republics into NATO were met with strong Russian opposition, which saw them as direct threats.
‚Ü™Ô∏é 2013-2014 Ukraine Crisis: In late 2013, Ukraine‚Äôs president suspended an EU Association Agreement under Western pressure, sparking protests (Maidan), which led to his ouster in February 2014. Russia viewed this as a coup; the West called it a revolution.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Crimea and Donbas: Russia annexed Crimea after a disputed referendum in March 2014. Pro-Russian unrest and referendums followed in Donbas, escalating the conflict.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Minsk Agreements: Attempts to resolve the conflict (Minsk I & II, 2015‚Äì2022) ultimately failed. Later, Western leaders like Merkel and Hollande admitted that Minsk was used to buy time for Ukraine to strengthen its military.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Western Military Aid: From 2014 to 2021, Western support for Ukraine grew from non-lethal aid to advanced weapons and intelligence, aligning Ukraine more closely with NATO.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Casualties: Around 13,000 combatants and civilians were killed in the Donbas from 2014 to 2021, largely due to Ukrainian shelling.
‚Ü™ Rejected Security Proposals: In December 2021, Russia proposed halting NATO expansion and restructuring European security, but the U.S. and NATO rejected these proposals.
‚Ü™ Recognition and Invasion: Russia recognized the Donetsk and Luhansk People‚Äôs Republics as independent in February 2022 and launched its ‚Äúspecial military operation‚Äù (SMO) in Ukraine, citing the UN Charter‚Äôs right to self-defense.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Peace Talks Blocked: In March 2022, British PM Boris Johnson reportedly discouraged Ukraine from signing the Istanbul Protocol, which would have included Ukrainian neutrality and security guarantees.
‚Ü™Ô∏é Further Annexations: Russia annexed four more Ukrainian regions (Donetsk, Luhansk, Kherson, Zaporizhzhia) in September 2022.

comment_text: On the Magura drone we can see two pylons usually for air to air missiles on a fighter jet but upside down. Those pylons usually have pusher systems, (a spring would not be enough in general it is gas or explosive system) to push away the ordinance, so just before the missile is ignited, the pusher system launches is vertically and probably strong enough to give is proper clearance for it to be able to fly away without first crashing into the sea. Those pushers are important on a fighter jet because it is those which avoid the bomb or missile tu be sucked in toward the jet itself by aerodynamic forces (with potential catastrophic outcome). This probably required a lot of work and experimentation in order to fine tune for reliable weapon firing in a completely different way. Very clever.

1. The vaunted Russian offensive... where is it? The Russians are now taking a beating around both Pokrovsk and Toretsk, yet they continue suicide attacks AND are losing ground. Losing ‚âà 1200 per day while going backward is no joke.  Was the intent that the forces that threw the Ukrainians back in Kursk would become a serious offensive? It's not happening. So.... ???

2. Putin's mobilization ... really? To be useful to Putin these conscripts must be induced or coerced into signing the contracts for combat in Ukraine... and then what does he have?  Nothing more than fresh meat.  Russia doesn't have the tanks, APCs, or much of the other supplies.  And these raw recruits can't be trained to be anything more than meat in time for this fighting season.    Looks to me like Putin's army is desperately close to collapse.  What is the counter-argument against that?

3. Ukraine's long-range drones are getting numerous and there is steady progress on enhanced capability.  How much of a beating can Russia take?

comment_text: The F16s being sent to Ukraine are from the US's "Boneyard" (309th Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Group) in Tucson, Arizona. The Boneyard does a bit of storage of old planes that could be rearmed and re-equipped for usage, as well as storage of old aircraft to be used for parts. Ukraine is receiving a few of these so called "parts planes". In recent years, a ton of the planes and helicopters have been rebuilt and sent into action from this storage facility.

Fun fact: A military parade usually only involves just 1% of a country's total troops. And these men who participates are chosen based on:
1) Height. Parade organizers would choose participants who would have about the same height for aesthetics;

comment_text: Thanks again for another great update, Denys.  In America, most people feel it is strange for Trump to be proclaiming new "Victory Days" for the end of WWI and WWII.  Since 1868, the USA has celebrated Memorial Day on 30 May and now the fourth Monday in May.  This federal holiday originally was held to honor the Union soldiers who died in the American Civil War; now it honors all military personnel that have died serving in any of America's wars.  Since the end of WWI in 1918 and the signing of the treaty in 1919, the USA has celebrated Veterans Day on 11 November, the date of Versailles Armistice  This federal holiday honors all currently serving and past members of the military in both peace and war time.  So the USA has been commemorating the end of WWI for 105 years... why do we need to change the name to Victory Day to appease Trump's ego?  And why do we need a second holiday in May celebrating the end of the European War in 1945?  Does this mean we should have an end of the Pacific war Victory Day on 2 September when Japan surrendered in 1945?  And Trump doesn't know history, he claims the USA "did more" to win these world wars than any other country.  How do we measure "did more"?  In Allied military and civilian deaths, Belarus lost 25% of their prewar population, Poland 17%, Ukraine, 16.5 %, the rest of the USSR 15%, France 2%, UK 1% and the USA 0.5%.  So instead of celebrating a victory, we should be focusing on the sacrifices made by all of our military personnel on our traditional Memorial Day and Veterans Day.

just a quick correction: ukraine is working towards artillery superiority, not supremacy.
supremacy would mean that russia has no artillery systems left to even fire back with. superiority means ukraine can fire more (and more accurate) than russia.

and, even after the GRAU deposit explosions and with the CZ-ammo program, for now artillery overall is roughly even. with how the russian push-system works, it will be probably two more weeks until the russian crews really feels the GRAU-incident. 

time will tell how (and from where) russia can acquisition artillery shells to make up for this loss.
if they cant, they will have 2 or 3 harsh months ahead, until restricted supplies will have cought up with production and things are back to normal for russian artillery.
dont get me wrong, that time is important, valuable and damn great for ukraine, but neitehr will it mean russia has no artillery left nor that they cant recouperate from it over a few months.
mistaking this for a "ukraine suddenly has superiority" is both wrong and dangerous for ukraine, because it could lead to careless decisionmaking.

comment_text: I am a 70 year old retired U.S. Army Master Sergeant (E8/1972-1993) and former defense contractor worker bee (2005-2010) who spent much of his career in the cold war. What we currently have in Ukraine is similar to the situation that existed for most of WWI on the west front: a stalemate with small gains won or lost by either side from day-to-day. Ukraine simply does not have enough equipment, forces or resources to take back the land they lost in 2022. On the flip side Russia no longer possesses the conventional forces needed to win the war on their terms as long as NATO nations continue to provide equipment and supplies to Ukraine. As for the lost land, Ukraine must accept the ground reality that the land they have lost to Russia is gone forever, especially the Crimea. The only way that could ever change would be if NATO directly intervenes in the war and fights Russia. If that were to happen, we would quickly move to WWIII and most likely a large nuclear exchange, so realistically I don't see such NATO intervention happening, as the stakes are just too high. The question at this point is how much more destruction and death must occur before both sides finally accept the truth that the current situation on the ground is as good as it going to get, and both sides finally end the war?  While personally I don't like to see Russia end the war with Ukrainian land as their ill-gotten gains, the war with it's ever increasing death and destruction must end before it at some point spirals further out of control and we end up in WWIII.
